  footnotes: []
english:
  title: In Praise of Magistrate Yun's Pacification of Namwon
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the fifth year of Seung'an, while I governed Wansan, Magistrate Yun was appointed Inspector and sent forth. The people of that region held him in reverence and fear. At that time, Namwon harbored unruly elements who gathered in bands, fortified themselves in the mountains, and plotted rebellion. The local officials, being weak and ineffectual, could not control them. They fled to report to the Inspector. That very day, the Magistrate rode in alone on a single horse, entered the prefecture, and explained to them the consequences of their actions—both ruin and salvation. Not a single bandit failed to be moved to tears and obedience. Thereupon he executed two or three ringleaders and pardoned the rest. Thus peace was restored, and the entire region rejoiced. Hearing of this, my admiration alone seemed insufficient, so I respectfully composed this short hymn and offer it from afar to the traveling sage.


    Daebang, the ancient commandery—
    Southern's rightful arm, it stands.
    Should one arm break and fall,
    How can the body endure?

    Wide the land, fierce the people;
    Waves of rebellion surge and rise.
    Hardened bandits gather,
    Plotting against the realm.
    They terrorize the common folk,
    Assemble thick as ants,
    Fortify themselves against the mountain's back,
    Wield weapons sharp as rhino horn.
    They sally forth to plunder,
    Reap sustenance from robbery.
    Their roots dig ever deeper,
    Hard now to uproot them.

    The elders tremble in dread,
    Flee like startled rabbits, like panicked deer.
    The magistrate and his deputy—
    Sweat pours down their faces like water.
    They rush to report to the Inspector,
    Words tumbling out with tears.

    The Magistrate speaks:
    "Why did you not prepare beforehand?
    When jade and tortoiseshell break in their cases,
    Whose shame is this but yours?
    Since you cannot restrain them,
    How can I stand idle?"

    That very day he departs,
    Rides forth on his single steed.
    With dignified presence he enters the prefecture,
    Swiftly summons the bandit chiefs,
    Commands them to step forward,
    And speaks to them of life and death.

    The bandits weep and surrender,
    Cast down their arms, throw away their spears.
    He executes only the conspirators,
    Spares the rest without inquiry.

    The countless bandits—
    Their hearts turn; they yearn for righteousness.
    All say: "We did not know ourselves,
    Like riders on wild horses
    We charged ahead, impossible to stop.
    Our strength could not prevail alone—
    We needed someone to hold the reins.
    Without such a man,
    Our bodies would have perished, our lives been lost.

    Alas, how we resemble that very plight!
    Had the Magistrate not intervened,
    Where would our feet have carried us?"

    The elders, given a second life,
    Dance and leap with joy.
    All proclaim: "Our lord and magistrate,
    You plucked us from the tiger's jaws.
    Our very heads—
    They are your gift to us."

    Praise echoes on the wind,
    Spread across a thousand miles.
    Great his deeds, lofty his name,
    Equal to heaven, level with earth.

    He who sings this song of praise
    Is but a humble official of Wansan.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 承安 (Seung'an) was the reign period of the Jurchen Jin Dynasty (1196-1220). Lee Gyubo lived during Goryeo's Goryeo period and this date reflects the historical context of the era.
  - key: ''
    value: Daebang (帶方) was an ancient name for the Namwon region, evoking historical significance.
  - key: ''
    value: The metaphor of the 'arm' represents the region's vital importance to the state—a broken arm renders the body dysfunctional.
  - key: ''
    value: The image of jade and tortoiseshell breaking in their cases (龜玉毁櫝) references an ancient Chinese saying about neglect and incompetence.
  - key: ''
    value: Lee Gyubo identifies himself as a 'humble official of Wansan' in his final line, expressing appropriate modesty while asserting his role as chronicler of this virtuous deed.
